Yes. Your code is basically a console/background worker, but the project is still initialized like a **Windows Forms app** using `Application.EnableVisualStyles()` and `Application.SetCompatibleTextRenderingDefault(false)` before the infinite loop. 

Do this in **2 parts**:

## 1. Change the project to Console Application

In Visual Studio:

**Project → Properties → Application → Output type → Console Application**

Or in the `.csproj`, make sure it is:

```xml
<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
```

Not:

```xml
<OutputType>WinExe</OutputType>
```

`WinExe` hides the console window.

---

## 2. Remove the WinForms startup code

Change your `Main()` from this:

```csharp
[STAThread]
public static void Main()
{
    Application.EnableVisualStyles();
    Application.SetCompatibleTextRenderingDefault(false);
    LoadGlobalSettings();

    string[] files = null;

    while (true)
    {
        ...
    }
}
```

To this:

```csharp
public static void Main()
{
    Directory.CreateDirectory(@"C:\logs");

    Console.Title = "UTF8 File Transformer";

    LoadGlobalSettings();

    logger.Info("UTF8 File Transformer started.");

    string[] files = null;

    while (true)
    {
        try
        {
            System.Threading.Thread.Sleep(Properties.Settings.Default.WAITVALUE);

            foreach (string subFolder in Properties.Settings.Default.SUB_FOLDERS)
            {
                try
                {
                    string folderPath = inputPath + pathSeparator + subFolder;

                    if (Directory.Exists(folderPath))
                    {
                        files = Directory.GetFiles(folderPath);

                        logger.Info(files.Length == 0
                            ? "No files found in the SubFolder: " + subFolder
                            : "SubFolder: " + subFolder + " Files to be converted to UTF-8 are: " + files.Length);

                        foreach (var file in files)
                        {
                            ConvertFileEncoding2Utf8(file, subFolder);
                        }
                    }
                    else
                    {
                        logger.Warn("Folder does not exist: " + folderPath);
                    }
                }
                catch (Exception ex)
                {
                    logger.Error(ex, inputPath + pathSeparator + subFolder + " try");
                }
            }
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            logger.Error(ex, "Unhandled error in main loop");
        }
    }
}
```

Also remove this using:

```csharp
using System.Windows.Forms;
```

You do not need it anymore.

---

## 3. Add console + file logging to NLog

In your `App.config`, add or update the `nlog` section like this:

```xml
<configuration>
  <configSections>
    <section name="nlog" type="NLog.Config.ConfigSectionHandler, NLog" />
  </configSections>

  <nlog xmlns="http://www.nlog-project.org/schemas/NLog.xsd"
        xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
        autoReload="true"
        throwExceptions="false"
        internalLogLevel="Trace"
        internalLogFile="C:\logs\utf8-transformer-nlog-internal.log">

    <targets>
      <target xsi:type="Console"
              name="console"
              layout="${longdate} ${level:uppercase=true} ${message} ${exception:format=tostring}" />

      <target xsi:type="File"
              name="file"
              fileName="C:\logs\utf8-transformer.log"
              archiveFileName="C:\logs\archive\utf8-transformer.{#}.log"
              archiveEvery="Day"
              archiveNumbering="Rolling"
              maxArchiveFiles="30"
              layout="${longdate} ${level:uppercase=true} ${logger} ${message} ${exception:format=tostring}" />
    </targets>

    <rules>
      <logger name="*" minlevel="Info" writeTo="console,file" />
    </rules>
  </nlog>

  <!-- keep your existing appSettings / userSettings here -->
</configuration>
```

Now every `logger.Info(...)`, `logger.Warn(...)`, and `logger.Error(...)` will appear in the console **and** in:

```text
C:\logs\utf8-transformer.log
```

---

## 4. Important checks if `C:\logs` is still empty

Run CMD as normal user and test:

```cmd
mkdir C:\logs
echo test > C:\logs\test.txt
```

If this fails, it is a permissions issue.

Also check this file:

```text
C:\logs\utf8-transformer-nlog-internal.log
```

That file will tell you why NLog failed, for example bad config, missing target, access denied, etc.

---

## Best final setup

Use:

```csharp
private static readonly Logger logger = LogManager.GetCurrentClassLogger();
```

Instead of:

```csharp
private static readonly Logger logger = LogManager.GetCurrentClassLogger(typeof(Program));
```

Both can work, but this is cleaner:

```csharp
private static readonly Logger logger = LogManager.GetCurrentClassLogger();
```

So the main fix is:

1. Change project output type to **Console Application**.
2. Remove `Application.EnableVisualStyles()` and `System.Windows.Forms`.
3. Add an NLog `Console` target.
4. Add an NLog `File` target pointing to `C:\logs`.
